 before a set of tests performed by Dr. Chalmers which had a BUN reading in the 99}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \cf6\super\insrsid539649 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid539649 
 percentile and elevated blood proteins.  A subsequent followup test a couple weeks later came back in the normal range.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10976062 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid539649 The nausea I had last fall\~ - which would be in phase IV \endash  was followed by severe pain over my liver and pain in the area of my right kidney.\~ Scans at the time showed nothing special. }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10976062 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \cf6\insrsid539649 During phase IV you also get the flushing of skin.\~ I think this is because the underlying layers of the epidermis are dying as explained above.\~ The exposed skin is actually much \'93newer\'94
 than would be typical and much closer to the blood flow as well as much easier to sunburn as well as staining due to the electrolytes being loaded in.\~ Additionally, the maximization of blood flow to the head is a contributor. As an experiment, I
\rquote ve been wearing spf 30 face lotion on }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\ul\cf6\insrsid539649 half}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid539649  my face since march or so, without any difference.\~ I am tanner now than in most years past.\~
 I now have zero crow\rquote s feet around my eyes at basically 43 years old.\~ At 40, I had them.\~ This is also due to the skin tightening aspect.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10976062 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid539649 The article also mentioned that during phase IV, the shrinking would disguise muscle weakness by increasing reflex conductivity and would also increase spinal strength by reducing the excess fluid.\~ }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10976062 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid539649 Additionally there were pictures of the fingernails.\~ They looked exactly like mine.\~ Essentially, the shrinking causes the tips of the fingers to lose blood flow and you get these lines behind
 the ends of your fingertips under the fingernails.\~ It actually hurts intermittently as the quick of the nail essentially separates from the finger.\~ But then, the line will disappear as the separated nail growth can be cut off.\~
 It said something about how nail color was normal, but that pressing on the underside of the finger would show something either the inelasticity of the finger pad (my finger pads now hold an indention if pressed) or the nail color darkening, I don
\rquote t remember honestly.\~ }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10976062 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid539649 Another thing is my blood pressure, while during Stage II my average pressure was generally 135/87 or so, during phase IV it has been 110/75 or so.\~\~
 Great to have the lower blood pressure as a rule, but something worth mentioning.\~ If I truly am experiencing anxiety or stress instead of having an illness, I would expect higher than normal blood pressure. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10976062 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid539649 Physical exertion of any significant amount (even a 20 minute scrimmage in soccer against my 5 year old), causes me to get a head ache right in the top of my head.\~ I\rquote 
ve had this type of headache during three periods \endash  1) in 1995 when I first when on the antifungal and would exert myself \endash 
 I will say it was wonderful then though, as the fog always lifted and I got really hungry, 2) Last July which was actually much worse due to the vision changes, and other issue, and 3) Now when I exert myself.\~
 Over the last month or so, I have gained about an inch in the stomach without changing weight or diet.\~\~ I know you the tests you performed should indicate that if it was present, however, this condition is insidious in how it works.\~ I don\rquote 
t know if the tests would be any different today \endash  in fact I don\rquote t think the tests would be the same at one time of the day as they are at another given how my days are cycling.\~ I\rquote m not asking for tests, I\rquote 
m just frankly venting.\~ }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10976062 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\cf6\insrsid539649 I do remember it did discuss measuring blood pressure standing versus sitting and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\cf20\insrsid539649 with a leg cuff }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\cf6\insrsid539649 during phase IV as a diagnostic screen}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid539649 .\~\~ I\rquote m not sure what would be the abnormal values, but it is something I remember.\~ pH testing wasn\rquote 
t a good tool due to how it is done. Somehow, actual pH differs from what you would expect given the normal electrolytes used to calculate it.\~
 Perhaps a simple pH strip or something less advanced would be better. Essentially, the body is in multiple metabolic conditions that all cancel each other out and make those tests less relevant.\~ Hormonal values obviously weren\rquote 
t helpful at least as of January when you tested.\~\~ I know this resembles the end stages of Addison\rquote 
s disease as I have all of the symptoms (exhaustion, weakness, tanning, changes in mental acuity, changes in blood sugar levels) just none of the significant clinical findings like electrolyte imbalances (at least as of January).\~
 That is why I feel I misspoke by referring to an earlier stage as pseudo-addisonian before. It is, in fact, this later stage that is such.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10976062 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid539649 What I am supposed to experience next is a continued worsening of this cycle.\~ Blood flow changes will eventually shut off all flow to the kidneys.\~
 If treated, the treatment is pretty horrible and the result is just a prolonging of the process.\~ If I can keep eating, eventually my pituitary will be unable to keep blood sugar levels down, this will lead to a resurgence in the candida infection 
which will cause more mental confusion and just snowballs the whole thing as it digests the sugars further straining the liver.\~ There were pictures of people with rotted appendages\~ in the article \endash 
 from the fungus. I think without treatment the outcome is the collapse of one of the veins coming from your leg which is evidently fatal \endash 
 or if you begin vomiting at any point (trust me, as of this week, I want to just about every moment but I have so much experience with nausea and there is so little bloodflow to my gut that I have yet to vomit once) if you begin vomiting it quickly spira
ls out of control and ends with a stroke.\~ With treatment \endash  which involves keeping blood sugars \'93as low as possible\'94
 first via insulin and later with direct injections of glucose (because the gut has shut down and cannot absorb/process foods) followed by adrenaline (and a subsequent ice bath due to body temperature rise), the eventual outcome is death via stroke but yo
u get to go blind first due to the surges in blood pressure during the treatments.\~ Antifungals don\rquote t help as most suppress the adrenal cortex, which is basically driving the bus at this point.\~
 And the infection will return anyway, as the body uses it to supply ATP to cells.\~ Sleep is out for all that, as the pressures are too high and sleeping itself would allow sugars to rise too much.\~\~
 Insulin injections cause the creation of water during the reaction with sugars which causes too much pressure as at this point the kidneys have all but quit.\~ Additionally, I remember it said almost word for word \'93
you would think that diuretics would be the solution but most diuretics cause narrowing of the blood vessels in the kidneys\'94 and somehow that made it worse.\~ It mentioned the recent advent of some potassium or sodium sparing diuretics, but I don
\rquote t remember what it said about that. So, of the options, I think I am better off with no treatment.\~ The article did say something strange about the very end, that the person would be extremely clear minded right at the end.\~ I don\rquote 
t remember if that was treated or untreated, but I found it interesting.\~ It makes sense, though, given what I am going through daily right now.\~ I can see where it would be at the peak of the circadian rhythm when the end came.\~
 The article said that once the patient stops eating, the fungus has a natural affinity for the hormones supplied by the pituitary and will eventually attack there resulting in a stroke.\~
 There were pictures of people eating cooked liver and spitting it out because they couldn\rquote t process it \endash 
 saying that making it that far had trained them to eat no matter what and that as their mouth was the only part of the body that could still absorb anything this was the best they could do.\~
 I will say that throughout the various episodes of nausea starting with the bad periods of phase II, eating was the only thing that cleared my head.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10976062 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid539649 Other possible treatments were discussed in the article and ruled out.\~ Hormone replacement wouldn\rquote t solve the other problems and wouldn\rquote 
t supply the high levels of hormones needed due to the adjustment of the body to the higher pressures to the head.\~ Heart transplant wouldn\rquote t work because at this point regular pressure to the brain wouldn\rquote t be enough, dialysis wouldn
\rquote 
t work to prevent the onset of phase IV due to the pH of the blood being different than the normal pH of someone that needs dialysis and the fact that the level needed to be maintained was well outside the ranged usually done. I know my pH tested normal, 
but it said something about the actual pH versus the calculated value based on CO3, I don\rquote t remember what.\~ }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10976062 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid539649 I\rquote ve said before that the patients were kept in a position such that their head was above their heart and their feet were\~ below their heart.\~ Essentially in a reclining chair.\~
 I think I mis-spoke before.\~ This was something to do with keeping some amount of blood flowing through the kidneys as well as being the best position for their heart.\~
 It said normally, in heart failure a different position was ideal but it was different in this case due to the blood pressure issues.\~ It also said the chair had a lever on them that the patients could flip that would cause their feet to be elevated.\~
 This was essentially giving up, as it would cause them to enter a \'93hypoglycemic coma\'94.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10976062 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid539649 
I will tell you this, when I was in the Laureate, the physical symptoms I was undergoing were so severe, I read that article and said to myself I would do whatever was needed to get those extra years, rather than die of a stroke that day or week, and let 
me tell you it was probably close, as I was so dehydrated my whole inside arm bruised when they drew blood, I could barely lift my legs, and my veins were literally having spasms\'85I could put my finger on one and watch it wiggle.\~
 So, I held my urine and drank a lot of caffeine and whatever I did was close enough to the shot of adrenaline that the book had said was the former treatment.\~\~ My outcome was a migraine like headache tha
t started slowly, lasted an hour or two and at the peak of it, I felt like I could hear a pin drop and every sound hurt.\~ Additionally, just wiggling a finger caused intense pain in my head.\~ }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10976062 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid539649 I get up every day even back then, force myself to do what has to be done and given that phase II is pretty uneventful, comparatively, I\rquote ve had a good life.\~
 It was good enough that I made myself believe that I didn\rquote t have what I knew I had.\~ There is no way I should\rquote 
ve ever doubted myself given the severity of what I had been through and the several times I had to take the antifungals and dehydrate myself to get back on track.\~
 It was just such a long gap since the last time and 2010 that I had convinced myself otherwise.\~ I won\rquote t be giving up.\~ I\rquote m not that guy.\~
 But, it is getting harder and my hope is that eventually there will at least BE a clinical diagnosis.\~ What I don\rquote t understand is how medical knowledge like this is \'93lost\'94.\~
 The article was so detailed, even though it stated it was rare, but there were pictures with many people with the same condition \endash  all in the reclining chairs.\~
 I understand that medicine progresses, and perhaps there was something that used to be done that is not anymore so the study of the result is no longer required, but it just seems strange to me.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10976062 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \cf6\insrsid539649 Anyway, I believe I am in the more final stages of this where there will be }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\cf6\insrsid539649 no more}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid539649  stable periods.\~
 If I am correct, then it should become evident in the near future.\~ I have had just about every test one could want at one point or another during all of this.\~ I do see a therapist every two weeks.\~\~ The last few months I\rquote 
ve felt weak, but pretty much normal otherwise \endash  very clear minded, it has been great.\~ Things are changing now.\~ I will face it head on.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10976062 
