\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid539649 
So, the theory is that Candida was in my body and the energy it supplied by processed sugars at the cellular level (ATP) allowed my body to sustain the phase III time during which intracellular electrolyte levels were slowly moving towards a level at whic
h the pituitary could no longer make the pancreas excrete insulin.\~ This was manifested by an increase in the fluid levels of the body in Phase III.\~ The sudde
n die off of Candida caused by the Fluconazole caused the electrolyte levels to quickly shift as the body threw off much more fluid than usual but was unable to excrete whichever electrolyte is the one that the kidneys no longer can due to the early kidne
y damage in stage I onset \endash  I will add that during stage II, the long healthy stage, the kidney damage is bypassed \~
by excreting the electrolyte through the feces due to the unusual pressure differential where veinous pressure exceeded arterial in the intestinal areas.\~ Also, I exe
rcised a lot running 5ks and the Tulsa Run etc, sweating profusely with regularity as well as donated blood fairly regularly because both made my head clearer \endash  until my doctor told me I was anemic and I stopped the donations.\~\~
 At some point, the intracellular electrolyte level is reached where insulin can no longer be caused to be secreted as the concentration cannot be increased further for some reason, so blood sugar levels rise quickly.\~
 This causes a large new supply of energy to the pituitary.\~ This in turn causes it to go into overdrive and take over sugar levels completely.\~ This was manifested first by nausea and then headaches and blurred vision.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10976062 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid539649 Several times since then I have briefly taken Fluconazole.\~ I would do this because the nausea had returned.\~
 My theory there is that the candida would return enough to cause nausea, the dose of Fluconazole would kill it off, and the sugar levels would rise until the pituitary was able to work even harder to keep down levels.\~
 This explains my post-prandial sugar levels of August \endash  fairly recently being sub \endash  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \cf6\insrsid539649 100 more like 75-80.\~ Now however, the pituitary or the heart or both are unable to work as hard.\~
 So, my sugar levels have been rising.\~ Four weeks ago when I wrote you, I had experienced the nausea and fogginess again \endash  my post prandial blood sugar was 115 }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid539649 \~\~
- normal I know, but not what I had been having for the previous 10 months.\~ So, I took Fluconazole not because of the sugar level, but because of the nausea and fogginess.\~ This had a rather dramatic effect within 36 hours.\~
 I first had the stomach cramping, then my head cleared up and the nausea mostly went away.\~ Over the next week, I had more energy than I have had over the last year, with some headaches and less severe stomach cramping.\~ The initial cramping, how
ever, was severe and extended into my chest and the back of my neck.\~ My theory here is that the sugar spiked as the candida was killed off, and the pituitary used the new energy to reduce volumes in order to be able to control the level.\~
 This resulted in some flow to my intestinal/organs being cut off \endash  the veinous flow.\~ This made it easier for my heart to pump blood and helped reduce sugar levels some.\~
 This is because basically the heart is sucking (literally not figuratively) and sucks so hard it closes off some of the flow \endash 
 the reason it is sucking so forcefully is the pituitary is causing it to through the manipulation of endorphins combined with vaso-dilaters and constrictors.\~ }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10976062 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid539649 So, that all sounds pretty elaborate, I know.\~ But there are other things that happen when I take the pill and the weird thing is that dosage I take is small.\~ My palms turn red and blotchy for one.}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10976062 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \cf6\insrsid539649 Anyway, I think from here it is going to get worse and more frequent, as while I have had a stable couple weeks, last week the nausea and fogginess returned \endash 
 this time my post prandial blood sugar was 129 (trend fairly established at this point from mid 70s to almost 130 all of which are documented in my glucometer).\~ So, I did the only thing I could do and took Fluconazole again on Friday/Saturday June 15}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \cf6\super\insrsid539649 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid539649  and 16th.\~
 It worked somewhat, but not as well, but I did not take as much as I did 4 weeks ago (100mg total over 2 days about half the previous amount which was over 4 days).\~ I have the headaches again though, and have been able to think more clearly and 
the nausea mostly went away, but already I am foggy, so I\rquote m not sure what I will do next.\~ I know if the nausea returns I will take it again.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10976062 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid539649 I anticipate that the cycle will worsen and eventually, I will have diabetic blood sugar levels.\~ I think this is what the article meant by the return to an acidic level for the cells of the body.\~ I
\rquote m assuming such high sugar levels will bring along higher acidity levels.\~ The article talked about how muscles would begin tearing as they were broken down by the changes\'85
This is another reason the people were confined to the chairs, as the muscles couldn\rquote t take normal exertions. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10976062 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \cf6\insrsid539649 
This is all why the article had the patient treated by keeping the blood sugar as low as possible because essentially each blood sugar peak is a one way step to the next higher level and each step results in reduced blood volume and other changes.\~ }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\cf6\insrsid539649 All the while, the electrolytes are kept in the normal range, as it is using molarity to control things and ignoring volume}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid539649 .\~
 That is the most significant part of the clinical equation \endash  and because of it everything appears fine in basic medical tests.\~ I can imagine some clinical things that might be different \endash 
 the blood pressure in the legs should show lower than expected, perhaps a fMRI of the brain, I don\rquote t know.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10976062 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid539649 However, I can only imagine how the patient does during these times.\~ The inability to concentrate is extraordinary.\~ They wouldn\rquote t be in pain, but they would be pretty mindless.\~ I\rquote 
ve already been there and I know I hate it.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10976062 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid539649 So, in my theory the path forward is a continued worsening with peaks that are only resolved by further reduction of flow to the bodies organs.\~
 This is why it said one path was the collapse of the major vein coming from a leg.\~ With treatment, you end up confined, with pressures escalating wi
th blindness, death of the intestinal tract, inability to think, etc until the candida either attacks the heart muscle or the pituitary directly.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10976062 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid539649 I know my body.\~ I\rquote ve lived with it a long time.\~ The things I\rquote 
ve described to you really happened and more, from the profuse urination in 1995, to the resolution of symptoms at times with a simple anti-fungal.\~ \~\~But, I also can tell that things are not what they used to be.\~
 I know with 100% certainty the seriousness of what is going on.\~ It will become clinically evident at some point, I think.\~ I just want that to occur such that my family can know.\~ }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10976062 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \cf6\insrsid539649 For what it\rquote s worth, I went to my doctor to report the stomach pains on June 4}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \cf6\super\insrsid539649 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid539649 .\~
 He did a CBC, Chem14 and TSH and said all were normal (I haven\rquote t seen the results, but I\rquote m sure he is right).\~
 He wanted to do a CT with and w/o contrast of my chest due to a nodule that has shown in the past, but I turned that down due to the iodine and the fact that the last time I had iodine in 2010 I went about 5 or 6 days without significant urination.\~}{
